How: The code in Gemini was implemented by creating a function that iterates through an inventory array and creates a new div for each entry.

Why: Gemini's Code was used because I needed an efficient way to dynamically generate and display HTML elements based on data stored in JavaScript objects rather than hard-coding them into the HTML file.

How: Gemini's Code was modified by changing the element type from a simple <li> to a <div> and adding a template literal string (backticks) to include multiple nested HTML tags like <h4>, <span>, and <p> to show more detailed item properties.

### Prompt Used on _NAME OF AI TOOL_

```Gemini - The AI Tool used
Copy and paste the prompt used

```Give me an example of using Set as to find the duplicate

The code prompt above was used [NAME](link) to generate the code shown below:

```
Copy and paste the entirety of the code generated by the AI Tool listed above.

```const inventoryNames = ["Potion", "Sword", "Potion", "Shield", "Sword"];
const seen = new Set();
const duplicates = [];

inventoryNames.forEach(item => {
  if (seen.has(item)) {
    // If we've seen it before, it's a duplicate
    duplicates.push(item);
  } else {
    // If it's new, add it to the "seen" Set
    seen.add(item);
  }
});

#### script.js

_Lines 178 - 193_

```
Copy and paste your code on the lines mentioned

```function findDuplicates() {
    const seen = new Set();
    const duplicates = new Set();
    inventory.forEach(item => {
        const identifier = `${item.name.toLowerCase()}-${item.type.toLowerCase()}`;
        if (seen.has(identifier)) {
            duplicates.add(identifier);
        } else {
            seen.add(identifier);
        }  
    });
    return Array.from(duplicates).map(id => {
        const [name, type] = id.split("-");
        return inventory.find(item => item.name.toLowerCase() === name && item.type.toLowerCase() === type);
    });
}
// Any duplicate items will be logged to the console, and if no duplicates are found, a message will indicate that as well.
const duplicateItems = findDuplicates();
if (duplicateItems.length > 0) {
    console.log("Duplicate items found:");
    duplicateItems.forEach(item => console.log(`- ${item.name} (${item.type})`));
} else {
    console.log("No duplicate items found.");
}

- <!---How---> The code in [NAME](link) was implemented by...
- <!---Why---> [NAME](link)'s Code was used because...
- <!---How---> [NAME](link)'s Code was modified by...
How: The code in Gemini was implemented by using a Set to track unique values while iterating through the inventory array to identify recurring items.Why: Gemini's Code was used because Set.has() provides a high-performance $O(1)$ lookup time compared to checking an array with indexOf(), making the duplicate detection much faster as the inventory grows.How: Gemini's Code was modified by creating a composite string identifier (combining name and type in lowercase) to ensure duplicates are caught based on multiple properties rather than just a single string, and by using Array.from().map() to return the actual object data rather than just the names.

